		<h2>Summary</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Requested in <span class="info">12</span>/<span class="info">26</span> calls</li>
			<li>Requested in <span class="info">9</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure calls (<a href="../sle2008/index.html#cfp">2008</a>–<a href="../sle2024/index.html#cfp">2024</a> with the longest streak of <span class="info">8</span> years)</li>

			<li>Primary tagged in <span class="info">12</span>/<span class="info">26</span> paper bundles</li>
			<li>Primary tagged in <span class="info">8</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure proceedings (<a href="../sle2008/index.html#lop">2008</a>–<a href="../sle2025/index.html#lop">2025</a> with the longest streak of <span class="info">5</span> years)</li>

			<li>Secondary tagged in <span class="info">14</span>/<span class="info">26</span> paper bundles</li>
			<li>Secondary tagged in <span class="info">11</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure proceedings (<a href="../sle2008/index.html#lop">2008</a>–<a href="../sle2023/index.html#lop">2023</a> with the longest streak of <span class="info">8</span> years)</li>
			<li>Top 3 co-occurring topics:
				<ul>
					<li><a href="t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a> (<span class="info">17</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a> (<span class="info">16</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a> (<span class="info">11</span> times)</li>
				</ul>
<li>Top 3 contributors:
				<ul>
					<li><a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a> (<span class="info">6</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a> (<span class="info">5</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a> (<span class="info">3</span> times)</li>
				</ul>

		</ul>

<h2>List of papers (48)</h2>
<ul>
<li><span class="info">(<a href="../atem2006s/index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../atem2006s/paper04.html">Learning Context-Free Grammar Rules from a Set of Program</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AlpanaDubey.html">Alpana Dubey</a>, <a href="../profile/PankajJalote.html">Pankaj Jalote</a>, <a href="../profile/ShubhaniAggarwal.html">Shubhani Aggarwal</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The core task is inferring missing context-free grammar rules (grammar completion) from program samples and an approximate grammar.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets reverse engineering of dialect grammars when documentation/manuals are missing, i.e., recovery of language definitions.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The approach is experimentally verified on multiple programming languages to demonstrate feasibility and effectiveness.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The inferred artefacts are CFG rules, i.e., meta-language objects used to define and generate parsers.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../atem2006s/index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../atem2006s/paper07.html">Evaluating Formal Properties of Feature Diagram Languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PatrickHeymans.html">Patrick Heymans</a>, <a href="../profile/PierreYvesSchobbens.html">Pierre-Yves Schobbens</a>, <a href="../profile/JeanChristopheTrigaux.html">Jean-Christophe Trigaux</a>, <a href="../profile/YvesBontemps.html">Yves Bontemps</a>, <a href="../profile/RaimundasMatulevičius.html">Raimundas Matulevičius</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasClaßen.html">Andreas Claßen</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" Feature diagrams are treated as variability modelling languages for software product lines, and the paper’s main focus is comparing their variability semantics.
">T2C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It grounds comparison in formal syntax/semantics (comparative semantics) and uses formal criteria to assess language properties.
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A substantial part is about (re-)engineering modelling languages by clarifying constructs/semantics and identifying ambiguities and expressiveness trade-offs.
">T1A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The method analyses and compares language definitions (FD notations) to discriminate between competing language designs.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2008/index.html">SLE 2008</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2008/paper02.html">Neon: A Library for Language Usage Analysis</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JurriaanHage.html">Jurriaan Hage</a>, <a href="../profile/PetervanKeeken.html">Peter van Keeken</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It presents a reusable library/tooling infrastructure for analyzing how a language is used in practice.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Its purpose is to support language-oriented analysis by extracting and aggregating usage information.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The usage-analysis capability is motivated as feedback for evolving and maintaining languages and their ecosystems.
">T2B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2008/index.html">SLE 2008</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2008/paper15.html">DeFacto: Language-Parametric Fact Extraction from Source Code</a></em> (<a href="../profile/HendrikusJSBasten.html">Hendrikus J. S. Basten</a>, <a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It provides language-parametric fact extraction that underpins systematic language/source-code analysis.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The contribution includes a reusable extraction/analysis infrastructure intended to be plugged into tools.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Language-parametricity and separable annotations enable reuse of the same extractor across many languages.
">T1E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2008/index.html">SLE 2008</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2008/paper17.html">Sudoku – A Language Description Case Study</a></em> (<a href="../profile/TerjeGjøsæter.html">Terje Gjøsæter</a>, <a href="../profile/IngelinFIsfeldt.html">Ingelin F. Isfeldt</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasPrinz.html">Andreas Prinz</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The ‘pearls’ framing makes it an experience-oriented report of language description practices.
">T6A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It is presented as a language-description case study, focusing on describing/analyzing a language precisely.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The Sudoku language description is effectively a DSL case illustrating language engineering choices.
">T3C</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2008/index.html">SLE 2008</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2008/paper18.html">The Java Programmer’s Phrase Book</a></em> (<a href="../profile/EinarWHøst.html">Einar W. Høst</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarteMØstvold.html">Bjarte M. Østvold</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It builds an automatically generated phrase book from a large corpus of Java programs, relying on empirical analysis of real-world usage.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It analyzes the structure and ‘semantics’ of method-name phrases, treating identifier naming as a describable language.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The motivation includes supporting developers as code and naming conventions evolve (e.g., guiding/refactoring names).
">T2B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2008s/index.html">SLE 2008 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2008s/paper03.html">Grammar Recovery from Parse Trees and Metrics-Guided Grammar Refactoring</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NicholasAKraft.html">Nicholas A. Kraft</a>, <a href="../profile/EdwardDuffy.html">Edward Duffy</a>, <a href="../profile/BrianAMalloy.html">Brian A. Malloy</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The work recovers and refactors a language grammar from an existing hard-coded parser and analyses the recovered grammar using grammar metrics.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Its methodology addresses recovery of an unavailable language artefact (the grammar) from existing implementations, which is an upwards vertical transformation.
">T4C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Context-free grammars are the central meta-language artefact being reconstructed and manipulated.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2010/index.html">SLE 2010</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2010/paper04.html">Metamodel Usage Analysis for Identifying Metamodel Improvements</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MarkusHerrmannsdörfer.html">Markus Herrmannsdörfer</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielRatiu.html">Daniel Ratiu</a>, <a href="../profile/MaximilianKoegel.html">Maximilian Koegel</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The work proposes analyses over metamodels and conforming models to detect mismatches and improvement opportunities.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The analyses are used to drive metamodel/language evolution via refactorings, constructors, and destructors.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It includes an empirical study over multiple metamodels and a corpus of models to validate the approach.
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2010/index.html">SLE 2010</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2010/paper09.html">An Extensive Catalog of Operators for the Coupled Evolution of Metamodels and Models</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MarkusHerrmannsdörfer.html">Markus Herrmannsdörfer</a>, <a href="../profile/SanderDVermolen.html">Sander D. Vermolen</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It provides a catalog of operators specifically for coupled evolution scenarios (metamodel + model co-adaptation).
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The operators essentially define systematic transformation steps for migration/co-evolution.
">T4B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The catalog organizes and characterizes change operators as a basis for analyzing and managing evolution.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2010/index.html">SLE 2010</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2010/paper11.html">A Unified Format for Language Documents</a></em> (<a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2e.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The focus is on representing and organizing language documentation in a unified, reusable format.
">T2E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It is oriented toward tool-supported processing/management of language documents (e.g., extracting/transforming artifacts).
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work treats language descriptions as analyzable/manipulable artifacts, enabling consistency and reuse checks.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2010/index.html">SLE 2010</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2010/paper12.html">Canonical Method Names for Java: Using Implementation Semantics to Identify Synonymous Verbs</a></em> (<a href="../profile/EinarWHøst.html">Einar W. Høst</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarteMØstvold.html">Bjarte M. Østvold</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The contribution is a language-oriented analysis of code to infer canonical method names from implementation semantics.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6g.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets developer-facing naming conventions and their cognitive/communication aspects in code bases.
">T6G</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The approach is validated empirically by mining/analyzing Java code and assessing synonym detection.
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2010/index.html">SLE 2010</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2010/paper19.html">Empirical Language Analysis in Software Linguistics</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JeanMarieFavre.html">Jean-Marie Favre</a>, <a href="../profile/DraganGašević.html">Dragan Gašević</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/EkaterinaPek.html">Ekaterina Pek</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The work is positioned around empirical methods for analyzing languages and their usage as data.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It treats language artifacts/utterances as objects of analysis in “software linguistics”.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2011/index.html">SLE 2011</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2011/paper14.html">Parse Forest Diagnostics with Dr. Ambiguity</a></em> (<a href="../profile/HendrikusJSBasten.html">Hendrikus J. S. Basten</a>, <a href="../profile/JurgenVinju.html">Jurgen Vinju</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It analyzes language descriptions (grammars/parsers) by diagnosing ambiguity in parse forests.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Dr. Ambiguity is a dedicated tool supporting this diagnostic workflow.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The setting is grounded in grammar formalisms and generalized parsing infrastructure.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2011/index.html">SLE 2011</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2011/paper15.html">Ambiguity Detection: Scaling to Scannerless</a></em> (<a href="../profile/HendrikusJSBasten.html">Hendrikus J. S. Basten</a>, <a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/JurgenVinju.html">Jurgen Vinju</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper’s main goal is detecting ambiguity in language definitions using scannerless parsing.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A key emphasis is scalability/performance when applying ambiguity detection at larger scale.
">T5F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The contribution is tied to parsing tooling and infrastructure for scannerless generalized parsing.
">T4A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2011/index.html">SLE 2011</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2011/paper16.html">Comparison of Context-Free Grammars Based on Parsing Generated Test Data</a></em> (<a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It proposes comparing grammars via automatically generated test data for parsers, i.e., a testing-based method.
">T5C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammar comparison is fundamentally an analysis task over language descriptions.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The approach depends on empirical evidence obtained by parsing generated inputs and comparing outcomes.
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2011/index.html">SLE 2011</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2011/paper17.html">RLSRunner: Linking Rascal with K for Program Analysis</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MarkHills.html">Mark Hills</a>, <a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/JurgenVinju.html">Jurgen Vinju</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" RLSRunner is a tool that integrates Rascal with K-based analyzers, functioning as a meta-tool/workbench component.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Both Rascal and K are meta-languages used to specify analyses and semantics.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The purpose of the integration is program analysis driven by language definitions and semantics.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012/index.html">SLE 2012</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012/keynote1.html">Analysing Contributions</a></em> (<a href="../profile/OegedeMoor.html">Oege de Moor</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The talk is centered on a concrete tool/product (ODASA) that integrates analyses and dashboards to support engineering work.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" ODASA’s core value proposition is large-scale software analysis over code, histories, and tooling outputs to surface “objective facts.”
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The emphasis on directing maintenance/testing effort and tracking quality trends over time squarely targets maintenance and evolution concerns.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The framing is explicitly industrial (product by Semmle Ltd for large projects; later acquired by GitHub, but that’s beyond what you provided).
">T6B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012/index.html">SLE 2012</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012/paper02.html">Profile-Based Abstraction and Analysis of Attribute Grammar Evaluation</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper analyzes properties of attribute-grammar evaluation (driven by profiling) to support understanding and optimization.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Profiling-based abstractions are used to reason about evaluation costs and performance bottlenecks.
">T5F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Attribute grammars are the underlying language-definition formalism being studied and characterized.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012/index.html">SLE 2012</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012/paper03.html">Termination Analysis for Higher-Order Attribute Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LijeshKrishnan.html">Lijesh Krishnan</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main contribution is a formal termination analysis technique for higher-order attribute grammars.
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets a meta-level correctness property (termination) of language definitions expressed as attribute grammars.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Higher-order attribute grammars are treated as a meta-language whose specifications are analyzed.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012/index.html">SLE 2012</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012/paper11.html">Grammatical Inference in Software Engineering: An Overview of the State of the Art</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AndrewWStevenson.html">Andrew W. Stevenson</a>, <a href="../profile/JamesRCordy.html">James R. Cordy</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper surveys grammar inference (learning grammars from data), which is an AI/ML-style technique applied to SLE tasks.
">T4G</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The inferred artifacts are grammars/language definitions, i.e., meta-language objects central to software language engineering.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It is concerned with recovering/analyzing language descriptions (grammars) from programs, traces, or other artifacts.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012/index.html">SLE 2012</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012/paper19.html">Modular Well-Definedness Analysis for Attribute Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/TedKaminski.html">Ted Kaminski</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The contribution is an analysis of language definitions (attribute grammars) ensuring completeness and non-circularity.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It is explicitly modular, enabling independent extension modules to be checked locally while guaranteeing global properties.
">T1D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work is grounded in an extensible attribute-grammar meta-language (Silver) and its modular composition model.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Ensuring well-definedness properties is a formal correctness task with conservative analyses and associated arguments.
">T5D</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012s/index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012s/paper03.html">A survey of grammatical inference in software engineering</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AndrewWStevenson.html">Andrew W. Stevenson</a>, <a href="../profile/JamesRCordy.html">James R. Cordy</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper surveys methods for inferring grammars from software artifacts, i.e., techniques for recovering and analysing language descriptions.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammatical inference is repeatedly discussed as a means for recovering undocumented or partially documented languages and formats from existing systems.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The survey is grounded in formal language/automata theory and learning-theoretic results that underpin inference approaches.
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A substantial part of the surveyed application space concerns DSLs and other software languages whose grammars are inferred for engineering purposes.
">T3C</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012s/index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012s/paper06.html">Monolithic and modular termination analyses for higher-order attribute grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LijeshKrishnan.html">Lijesh Krishnan</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper develops static analyses for attribute grammar specifications (termination of higher-order attribute evaluation), i.e., analysis of language descriptions.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It provides a sound (though incomplete) termination argument based on term-rewriting abstractions and correctness reasoning.
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The modular analysis is explicitly motivated by independently-developed language extensions and their safe composition.
">T1D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The analyses are implemented in and evaluated within an attribute-grammar system/tooling ecosystem (Silver/ableJ).
">T4A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2013/index.html">SLE 2013</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2013/paper06.html">Micropatterns in Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper introduces and studies “micropatterns” to analyze and comprehend grammar-like language descriptions (parsers, metamodels, data models).
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It treats grammars and related schema formalisms as meta-languages whose structure can be characterized and compared.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Identifying recurring structural fragments supports grammar comprehension and can inform maintenance/evolution of grammarware artifacts.
">T2B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2013/index.html">SLE 2013</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2013/paper08.html">Detecting Ambiguity in Programming Language Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NaveneethaVasudevan.html">Naveneetha Vasudevan</a>, <a href="../profile/LaurenceTratt.html">Laurence Tratt</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main contribution is an analysis technique for detecting ambiguity in context-free grammars for programming languages.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The paper emphasizes evaluation via generated/random grammars (Boltzmann sampling, mutation) to test ambiguity-detection techniques at scale.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammars are the analyzed artifacts, and the techniques operate at the level of grammar specifications.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2013/index.html">SLE 2013</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2013/paper13.html">Method and Tool Support for Classifying Software Languages with Wikipedia</a></em> (<a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/DominikMosen.html">Dominik Mosen</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreiVaranovich.html">Andrei Varanovich</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t3e.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main contribution is a method/tool for building a classification (taxonomy/ontology-like structure) of software languages using Wikipedia categories.
">T3E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The tool visualizes the extracted Wikipedia category graph in a navigable, tree-like form to support exploration and understanding.
">T4F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It performs analysis/mining over a large knowledge base (Wikipedia) to derive and refine language-classification structures.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2013/index.html">SLE 2013</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2013/paper16.html">Circular Higher-Order Reference Attribute Grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/EmmaSöderberg.html">Emma Söderberg</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper advances attribute-grammar technology (higher-order RAGs with circularity/rewrites), i.e., a core meta-language for language implementation.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A central concern is well-defined evaluation in the presence of interacting features (circularity and rewrites), i.e., analysis of language-definition behavior.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It studies how declarative rewrites and circular attributes interact, touching on compositional coordination between specification mechanisms.
">T1D</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2013/index.html">SLE 2013</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2013/poster1.html">Guided Grammar Convergence</a></em> (<a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main contribution is analysis and reconciliation of language descriptions (grammars) via milestones of identity/equivalence and structural matching.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It aims to infer (bidirectional) transformation steps between different grammar representations, i.e., mappings/conversions across formalisms.
">T4B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The entire setting is about meta-languages for syntax/grammar specification (grammars “in a broad sense”), including normalization to a normal form.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Conventional and guided convergence are explicitly framed as sequences of grammar transformation steps (including automatically inferred ones).
">T3B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014/index.html">SLE 2014</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014/paper04.html">Bounded Seas: Island Parsing Without Shipwrecks</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JanKurš.html">Jan Kurš</a>, <a href="../profile/MirceaLungu.html">Mircea Lungu</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarNierstrasz.html">Oscar Nierstrasz</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The core contribution is a parsing technique (island grammars) for robust/partial language processing.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It supports error recovery and robust parsing when dealing with incomplete or noisy source input.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The technique is motivated by practical manipulation of general-purpose programming language code.
">T3D</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014/index.html">SLE 2014</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014/paper05.html">Eco: A Language Composition Editor</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LukasDiekmann.html">Lukas Diekmann</a>, <a href="../profile/LaurenceTratt.html">Laurence Tratt</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It presents an editor/IDE prototype supporting composed languages via incremental parsing.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A main goal is modular language composition (combining arbitrary syntaxes).
">T1D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It extends incremental parsing and name binding analysis to support composed syntaxes.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It aims to preserve the feel of a normal text editor while guaranteeing structurally valid edits.
">T5H</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014/index.html">SLE 2014</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014/paper15.html">Simple, Efficient, Sound and Complete Combinator Parsing for All Context-Free Grammars, Using an Oracle</a></em> (<a href="../profile/TomRidge.html">Tom Ridge</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper advances parsing technology for context-free grammars via parser combinators.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It focuses on improving the efficiency/performance of sound-and-complete combinator parsing.
">T5F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It builds on prior formal soundness/completeness results (e.g., mechanized in a theorem prover).
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Parser combinators are a metalanguage/embedded formalism for specifying parsers from grammars.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014/index.html">SLE 2014</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014/paper19.html">Test-Data Generation for Xtext (Tool Paper)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JohannesHärtel.html">Johannes Härtel</a>, <a href="../profile/LukasHärtel.html">Lukas Härtel</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The contribution is a method and tool for grammar-based test-data generation for Xtext languages.
">T5C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets tooling support around Xtext language development and testing.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It uses a DSL for grammar transformation to customize grammars for test-data generation.
">T3B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It relies on grammatical structure (parse trees/choices) and language descriptions to drive generation.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014s/index.html">SLE 2014 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014s/paper04.html">Intra- and interdiagram consistency checking of behavioral multiview models</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PetraRadeljakKaufmann.html">Petra Radeljak Kaufmann</a>, <a href="../profile/MartinKronegger.html">Martin Kronegger</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasPfandler.html">Andreas Pfandler</a>, <a href="../profile/MartinaSeidl.html">Martina Seidl</a>, <a href="../profile/MagdalenaWidl.html">Magdalena Widl</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The contribution is a formal consistency-checking method for behavioral models (with SAT solving as the underlying decision procedure).
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It analyses language artifacts (behavioral UML models/diagrams) to detect and explain inconsistencies across views.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work targets a domain/purpose-specific modeling setting (behavioral multiview models) rather than general-purpose programming.
">T3C</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2015/index.html">SLE 2015</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2015/keynote1.html">What’s the value of an end user? Platforms and Research: The case of Pharo and Moose</a></em> (<a href="../profile/StéphaneDucasse.html">Stéphane Ducasse</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The keynote is explicitly about building and evolving research platforms (language + analysis platform) as language-engineering infrastructure.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Pharo is a general-purpose programming language platform, and language/platform design is a recurring theme.
">T3D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Moose is fundamentally about program/software analysis, and several cited results revolve around analyzing code and histories.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Topics like dynamic core updates and (especially) automated migration-rule generation are directly about evolution and maintenance over time.
">T2B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2015/index.html">SLE 2015</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2015/paper06.html">Reference attribute grammar controlled graph rewriting: motivation and overview</a></em> (<a href="../profile/ChristoffBürger.html">Christoff Bürger</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It is centered on semantic analyses implemented via reference attribute grammars (a static-semantics technique).
">T1B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Reference attribute grammars act as a meta-language for specifying analyses over structured syntax trees/graphs.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The paper discusses analysis of language descriptions/attributed specifications and how they control rewriting.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Graph rewriting is used as a transformation mechanism controlled by the attributed specification.
">T4B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2015/index.html">SLE 2015</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2015/paper12.html">Using decision rules for solving conflicts in extended feature models</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LinaOchoa.html">Lina Ochoa</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarGonzálezRojas.html">Oscar González-Rojas</a>, <a href="../profile/ThomasThüm.html">Thomas Thüm</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper addresses variability management and conflict resolution in feature models for product lines.
">T2C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It uses model-based transformation/processing to analyze or resolve feature-model conflicts.
">T4B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Conflict detection/resolution is formulated as analysis over the feature-model language description.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work typically includes evaluation on feature models/scenarios to demonstrate effectiveness (as implied by decision-making scenarios).
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2015/index.html">SLE 2015</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2015/paper13.html">Analysis and transformation with the nuthatch tree-walking library</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AnyaHeleneBagge.html">Anya Helene Bagge</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagM" title=" Nuthatch is presented as a reusable library/API for tree traversal, analysis, and rewriting.
">T3F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Its core capabilities include specifying and executing transformations/rewrites over trees.
">T3B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A primary application is program analysis by traversing and collecting information from trees.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" As a software library for language processing, it supports building language engineering tooling.
">T4A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2016/index.html">SLE 2016</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2016/paper02.html">Taming Context-Sensitive Languages with Principled Stateful Parsing</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NicolasLaurent.html">Nicolas Laurent</a>, <a href="../profile/KimMens.html">Kim Mens</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper proposes a principled runtime parsing technique (stateful parsing) to handle context-sensitive features.
">T4D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets language design realities where mainstream languages embed context-sensitive constructs.
">T1A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It formalizes how context-sensitive parsing concerns can be captured in the language description/grammar.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2016/index.html">SLE 2016</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2016/paper09.html">Language Design and Implementation for the Domain of Coding Conventions</a></em> (<a href="../profile/BoryanaGoncharenko.html">Boryana Goncharenko</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It designs a DSL to specify coding conventions as first-class language artifacts.
">T3C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Coding conventions are enforced through static constraints/semantic checks over programs.
">T1B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It analyzes programs/language instances against a formalized convention description.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2016/index.html">SLE 2016</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2016/paper16.html">DrAST: An Inspection Tool for Attributed Syntax Trees (Tool Demo)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JoelLindholm.html">Joel Lindholm</a>, <a href="../profile/JohanThorsberg.html">Johan Thorsberg</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" DrAST is a tool for inspecting attributed syntax trees, i.e., language implementation tooling.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Attributed syntax trees/attribute grammars often encode static semantics, which the tool helps understand and debug.
">T1B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It supports analysis/debugging of language specifications and their attributed tree structures.
">T5B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2017/index.html">SLE 2017</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2017/paper13.html">Towards a taxonomy of grammar smells</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MatsStijlaart.html">Mats Stijlaart</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It proposes a taxonomy of grammar smells, i.e., systematic analysis of grammar/language descriptions.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammar smells are motivated by grammar refactoring and maintenance of evolving language definitions.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The objects analyzed are grammars, which are meta-language artifacts used to define syntax.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A taxonomy supports building analysis/refactoring tools for grammars, which the paper discusses as a motivation.
">T4A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2017/index.html">SLE 2017</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2017/paper17.html">Deep priority conflicts in the wild: a pilot study</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LuísEduardodeSouzaAmorim.html">Luís Eduardo de Souza Amorim</a>, <a href="../profile/MichaelJSteindorfer.html">Michael J. Steindorfer</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It is a pilot study of deep priority conflicts found in real-world grammars.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The subject matter is analysis of grammar specifications to identify and characterize conflicts.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Such conflicts motivate grammar refactoring and long-term maintenance of language definitions.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The analyzed artifacts are context-free grammars, i.e., meta-language descriptions of syntax.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2022/index.html">SLE 2022</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2022/paper23.html">Partial Loading of Repository-Based Models through Static Analysis</a></em> (<a href="../profile/SorourJahanbin.html">Sorour Jahanbin</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/SimosGerasimou.html">Simos Gerasimou</a>, <a href="../profile/GersonSunyé.html">Gerson Sunyé</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main goal is improving scalability (time/memory) of model management via partial loading.
">T5F</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It uses static analysis of model management programs to determine what to load.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It generates graph-database (Cypher) queries that map model-management needs to repository retrieval.
">T4B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work targets model management/transformation/validation languages and their execution engines.
">T3B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2023/index.html">SLE 2023</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2023/paper07.html">Automated Extraction of Grammar Optimization Rule Configurations for Metamodel-Grammar Co-evolution</a></em> (<a href="../profile/WeixingZhang.html">Weixing Zhang</a>, <a href="../profile/ReginaHebig.html">Regina Hebig</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielStrüber.html">Daniel Strüber</a>, <a href="../profile/JanPhilippSteghöfer.html">Jan-Philipp Steghöfer</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The focus is on supporting co-evolution of metamodels and grammars by automatically extracting and updating grammar optimization configurations.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The technique analyses and manipulates grammar specifications to recover optimization-rule configurations.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammar migration after metamodel changes is framed as a systematic transformation/mapping problem between artefacts.
">T4B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2024s/index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2024s/paper08.html">Spectrum-based rule- and item-level localization of faults in context-free grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MoeketsiRaselimo.html">Moeketsi Raselimo</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main goal is diagnosing faults in language definitions (context-free grammars) by ranking suspicious rules/items using collected “grammar spectra.”
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The method is spectrum-based fault localization driven by test suites and instrumented/synthesized parsing runs.
">T5C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The approach is evaluated at scale on seeded-fault grammars across parsers/test suites/ranking metrics, reporting localization effectiveness.
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2024s/index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2024s/paper09.html">Property probes: Live exploration of program analysis results</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AntonRisbergAlaküla.html">Anton Risberg Alaküla</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a>, <a href="../profile/NiklasFors.html">Niklas Fors</a>, <a href="../profile/AdrianPop.html">Adrian Pop</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The core contribution is CodeProber, a tool mechanism (“property probes”) for interactively exploring program analysis results tied to AST nodes.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It supports debugging/understanding static analyses (e.g., attribute-grammar/RAG-based analyses) by inspecting computed properties on program representations.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The emphasis on interactive, live feedback in an editor makes usability and developer experience a primary concern.
">T5H</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The paper includes performance measurements showing probe overhead is negligible in the evaluated settings.
">T5F</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2024s/index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2024s/paper10.html">Grammar-based test suite construction using coverage-directed algorithms over LR-graphs</a></em> (<a href="../profile/ChristoffRossouw.html">Christoff Rossouw</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The contribution is an algorithm for generating grammar-based test suites that satisfy coverage criteria via LR-automaton graph exploration.
">T5C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It relies on analysis of grammar-derived LR automata/graphs (push/pop edges, conflicts) to guide construction of valid derivations.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The paper empirically evaluates efficiency/effectiveness (including comparisons to prior LR-graph exploration approaches).
">T5E</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2025/index.html">SLE 2025</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2025/paper12.html">Dynamic Dependency-Based Purity Checking</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AntonRisbergAlaküla.html">Anton Risberg Alaküla</a>, <a href="../profile/NiklasFors.html">Niklas Fors</a>, <a href="../profile/ChristophReichenbach.html">Christoph Reichenbach</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" It analyses and checks semantic properties (purity/side effects) of embedded code fragments in language specifications.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The target setting is reference attribute grammars in JastAdd, a meta-language ecosystem for language definitions.
">T3A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Tragdor is delivered as a tool that instruments/runs specifications to detect property violations dynamically.
">T4A</span></a></li></ul>
